<br>
If I vote for my state representative, or governer, or whoever, as I understand it, there is no other citizen who's vote is granted more weight than mine.<br>
<br>
But in the vote for President, a farmer in Wyoming has more say than I do. <br>
<br>
As for your lion -vs- Ewe argument...<br>
<br>
If 10% of the country votes for a Green party candidate, chances are high that 0% of the votes actually cast for president will be for that Green party candidate... how exactly is that giving the Ewe a stronger voice?<br>
<br>
And as for states having a voice (in regards to the Senate)... why?  Why should some open stretch of wind and rock like Wyoming have equal say in matters to a state like California?  I'm sure there's a fear that if they lost that voice that we'd just vote to turn Wyoming into a giant windfarm to power the rest of the US... but so? Why not?  If that really is the direction Wyoming needs to go why cripple the US as a whole for so vague a concept of Wyoming itself having a voice?<br>
