The President of the United States is the only nationally elected office at all.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr> If I vote for my state representative, or governer, or whoever, as I understand it, there is no other citizen who's vote is granted more weight than mine. <hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
The way those States hold elections is also not mandated by the Constitution.  Hence we have Primary and Caucus states, for example.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr> But in the vote for President, a farmer in Wyoming has more say than I do. <hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
Not really true, although I suppose it could be viewed that way.  The Presidential Election as it stands now, is really 50 separate Elections.  When you vote for the President of the US, you are actually voting for which candidate your STATE will select in the actual Presidential Election.  In reality your vote is the same as anyone else's vote...it is just that the States are disproportional. <br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr> And as for states having a voice (in regards to the Senate)... why? Why should some open stretch of wind and rock like Wyoming have equal say in matters to a state like California?  <hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
Well, although we have moved steadily away from this model over the last few hundred years, it is because the United STATES is comprised of a UNION of individual and sovereign STATES.  People used to think of themselves as being State Citizens first, and Nationally as a secondary consideration.<br>
<br>
I think this country is large enough, and diverse enough, that the ability of States to Govern should be supported.  Probably a very large number of people can't even name their Governor, let along State Representatives, and we see even States like California reduced to pathetic mockeries of Government with this Recall fiasco.<br>
<br>
